4 DAYS UNTIL SELFHEALERS CIRCLE ENROLLMENT 🎉

Thanks to member feedback, we’ve spent the past year building our own hosting platform. It’s easier to navigate + we now have a private community outside of facebook. Members are loving our new space.

The cost is $26/month or $286/year (one month free). My goal has always been to make the Circle affordable + accessible.

Enrollment will open January 1st at 12pm PST. Spaces are limited + do SELL OUT quickly. If you’re on the waitlist, you’ll be sent a link a few moments before enrollment opens. It might be helpful to set an alarm. There are currently 30,000+ people on the waitlist.

To find complete details on what the circle is all about, click the link in my bio. You can also add yourself to the waitlist.

I’ll see you in the ⭕️ + cannot wait for your healing journey to begin! selfhealers

node.text: Today it’s a true honor to talk to @dr.editheger— I’m actually a bit overwhelmed post filming this. Edith is a psychologist + Holocaust survivor who just released the book “The Gift.” I got chills throughout the book + know members of this community will love every word. Edith is an embodied teacher who gifts us with the wisdom that we are not not victims of our past, but powerful creators of our future. Her story is a testament to our true human potential. She’s a gift. I hope you all enjoy #selfhealers

Im moving. 

I spent over a year in Los Angeles. 

For the past few months, my nervous system has been craving more peace. More space. And more quiet. 

Tomorrow is the start of a new adventure. There will be a short pause on @selfhealers.soundboard as we move + set up our new studio. 

Let’s play guess where I’m moving. Fun fact: I’ve actually never been there 😂 #selfhealers

node.text:
Awakening is understanding we have a voice in our mind that is the ego.

It has an endless stream of opinions, ‘truths’ + beliefs about who we are + who other people are.

It’s our protector— keeping us in the familiar cycles we grew up in. 

When we become aware of the ego, we can understand we are not our thoughts. We aren’t our opinions. We aren’t our past. We aren’t our endless stream of identities.

This is how we become free from our own suffering (much of our suffering doesn’t actually come from the events we experience— it comes from the meaning we assign to those experiences.

Our egos have been working hard to protect us— they just need love + guidance #selfhealers

I’m in the process of writing the proposal on my next book 🎉

It’s about relationships + I’m heavy into the research phase. So you’ll be seeing a lot more relationship content.

Relationship empowerment is pretty much counter culture to everything we have been taught. Most of us are focused on changing our partners— + most of us are unconscious to the reality that we are doing this. 

This is the ego.

The ego loves to blame, deflect, + project. And many times it feels temporarily ‘good.’ Ultimately, it feeling helpless, misunderstood, + disempowered— just as most of is did in childhood. 

The truth is, in our childhood attachments we didn’t have choice. We had parent figures who violated our boundaries, who couldn’t emotionally connect with us, who were distracted by their own issues/relationships leaving them unable to even see us.

As adults healing from this wounding means finding choice.

It means looking at each situation + saying:

“What can I do with the information I have about this person/situation?”

“What role do my own beliefs/ego stories about this person/situation play?”

“What choice can I make in this moment for my inner child who didn’t have the opportunity to choose?”

“What childhood dynamics can I heal from that lead me to these relationship patterns?”

“What boundaries do I have or not have within my life?”

Relationship empowerment brings confidence. It comes from the awareness that we co-create our relationships. 

It comes from the awareness that the most important relationship is the one we have with ourselves. 

The relationship we have with ourselves creates how we feel about ourselves + how we feel about ourselves impacts every relationship we have #selfhealers

node.text:
Most of us go into relationships with healing to do. 

We have known or witnessed versions of love that included control, unconscious manipulation, shaming, + emotional abandonment.

We are attracted to relationships that have traits similar to the traits/dynamics we had within our childhood. We repeat these cycles because the subconscious mind has learned: love looks like ‘x.’

Consciously choosing relationships is the act of tuning into your own inner world. 

It’s the practice of being aware of how your body/nervous system responds. It’s the awareness of how that person speaks (while witnessing the actions that person takes.) 

Many people ‘tell us what we want to hear’— actions do not lie. 

Awareness of actions is relationship empowerment. 

Relationship empowerment allows us to create relationships that are safe, secure, + allow for mutual evolution. 

Relationship empowerment allows us to navigate relationships not as the wounded child self who seeks to be chosen, but as the wise adult who seeks to grow + become the highest version of Self.

Are you empowered in your relationships? #selfhealers

node.text:
Breakups can be emotionally devastating.

Even if we know our partner wasn’t a good match. Even if we felt unhappy, unfulfilled, unseen, or unacknowledged. Even if we were chasing “potential” or if we never got our partner to fully emotionally commit. (Actually, especially if we didn’t get that emotional connection.) 

Some of us shame ourselves for this, and the truth is our feelings go much deeper than the relationship.

Breakups trigger our core childhood attachment wounding.

They are the closest, most intimate relationships we experience— + that brings up everything that the mind + body remembers from our the first relationship we experience: the one with our parent figures.

Most of us have unresolved wounding from those first relationships. Many of us weren’t seen, heard, or able to fully express ourselves. We didn’t get emotional connection. We were unconsciously forced into playing a role + to betraying or denying our needs to gain the love or approval of a parent.

When we breakup, childhood wounding floods to the surface— all the core beliefs we developed as children “no one will choose me” “no one will stay” “everyone leaves” “I’m not worthy of being loved” seem to be true. 

We feel the same pain we felt with our partners as we did with our parents. Broken, misunderstood, + alone.

Emotions will be highly activated when relationships ends— regardless of how that relationship looked. 

And that’s ok. Not all of these emotions means something (we should get back together, I made a mistake, I should have been more x).

You are grieving more than one loss. Love yourself through it.

‘Getting over it’ isn’t about replacing the person, it’s about healing the original wound #selfhealers

node.text:
If you read one caption of mine read this one:

I’ve spent a lot of time reading all of your comments + the Q&A about the way people have shamed you.

I am not at all surprised by the way people have been spoken to by parent figures (who were also spoken to the same way by their own parents.) 

It’s no wonder our world is full of such frustration + pain.

We truly are a traumatized collective. 

Many of us are told by the people we love most that are bodies need fixing, that people won’t choose us, that we bring shame to our family, that who we are as human beings is not good enough.

Sometimes we are unconsciously manipulated:

“You’re going to kill me”
“You’ll miss me when I’m gone”
“If you loved our family, you would do/be/say x”
“That never happened, you have a big imagination”
“If he touched you, you brought it on yourself.”
“Why can’t you just be like x”
“Why are you so difficult?”

We all need to heal. 

We need to become conscious to when we are shaming ourselves + other people. 

We need to begin the practice of self acceptance, of curiosity, of releasing control around how someone should be + letting them BE.

I hope these scripts are helpful for you + I hope that as you practice/exist within the world you understand that people who shame are living within deep shame themselves.

Remember:
1. You have a right to be whoever you wish to be regardless of the discomfort it brings up in others 

2. You have a right to speak on/share whatever you feel called to speak on 

3. Your life choices are for you to make
 
4. Leaving family or cultural norms that are causing you pain is not betrayal 

5. Observe the messenger— if they don’t have the life/emotional state you wish to have, weigh their statements accordingly

6. People who believe in themselves, believe in the best within others. 

7. People who have been taught to not believe in themselves, will attempt to control, hurt, + limit others #selfhealers

node.text:
As you become more conscious, you’ll know when someone is attempting to project shame onto you.

The ego will immediately become defensive— ego remembers every time it’s been shamed in the past + comes in swinging.

This is why when most people are shamed, they shame the person back. Ironically, this will only cause US more shame because when we shame others, we feel that shame too. We’ve acted outside of our true nature. 

And while it might feel good temporarily, it always leads to regret. 

Healing is about understanding that secure, emotionally healthy people do not shame others.

They are curious. They openly communicate. They ask questions. They’re committed to their own learning + to learning another perspective.

Shaming is a commitment to misunderstanding any perspective outside of our own. 

When we respond to shaming with clear boundaries, we become more confident.

Rather than shaming back, we allow a person their own perspective. We don’t take on this perspective or allow it to become our truth.

We heal when we are conscious, we pause, + we react in new ways (that will be very uncomfortable at first) #selfhealers

node.text:
A vast majority of us have been shamed as children, so shaming others is incredibly common— most people are unaware they’re even doing it.

When we carry shame about our past + who we are as a person, many of us project that shame onto others. 

Shame projections are when someone let you know they disapprove of you or your actions in some way. 

Usually the person engaging in this has issues communicating their true feelings which would sound like:
“I’m scared” 
“this feels uncomfortable” 
“I miss you” 
“when you did that I felt abandoned.” 
“I heard something confusing about you, can you help me understand?”
“I’m insecure + am afraid of how others will judge the family.”

So they speak in the same way they were once spoken to.

As we heal, we are aware of when we are shaming ourselves/others approach situations with more curiosity + non judgment.

It’s helpful to remember that people who are speaking this way are dealing with their own pain + are not actually attempting to understand you or the situation.

Boundaries are key.

We create our own suffering when we attempt to change other people’s perspective of who we are.

We create healing when we know our truth, when we engage in consistent actions around that truth, + when we see shaming for what it is: deep inner pain protected outwards #selfhealers

node.text:
Body image has nothing to do with our physical appearance.

Body image lives within the mind. 

It’s the internalized thoughts, beliefs, preferences that we were either directly told or heard in childhood.

Our parent figures have the greatest impact on our own body image. 

How they speak about their bodies, speak about other people’s bodies, + our own body becomes our body image.

When we reach school age, have peers who also project ideas about body image (the same ideas they’ve heard at home.) 

We also get messages from media (the collective body image) that reinforces the same ideas heard within our homes.

I’m still in the process of learning to love my body. 

For me, it was helpful to go back to my moms messaging of her own body. She always struggled with weight. She also always commented on the weight of other women. How they’d put on weight. How they’d lost weight. On my sisters weight. I was conscious from a young age that appearance was very important + spoken about often.

Diets were also incredibly common in my home. Crash diets— *not* addressing nutrition, or eating through listening to the body. Losing weight was always a goal, but actually feeling good was not spoken of.

The message: the body is only to be loved + accepted at a specific weight. When the body is not that weight, it’s hated or loathed, or rejected.

How did you hear your parent figures speak about weight, their bodies, + your body? #selfhealers
